## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Remove entirely |

### Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` â€” the runtime no longer supports forcibly injecting exceptions into threads. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable â€” always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

            // Block until the task completes or the timeout fires.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls for This Migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work won't stop by itself** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancelling a token doesn't interrupt running code. If `work()` is a long CPU loop, it keeps running after the timeout â€” you've only stopped *waiting*. To actually stop it, pass the token into `work` and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* timeout, not an unrelated cancellation. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` inside work** | Won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. |

### If the work must actually stop (recommended)

Accept a `CancellationToken` so callers can pass it through:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}

// Caller example â€” work cooperates with cancellation:
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return items.Count;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### What was removed

| .NET Framework API | Status in .NET 8 |
|--------------------|------------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006` |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Replace with `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006` |
| Manual `new Thread()` + `Join()` | Replaced by `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` |

### Uncooperative code (last resort)

If `work` is code you **cannot modify** (e.g., third-party library, native call), no in-process mechanism can forcibly stop it. Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout.
